{
  "doc_id": "8086",
  "text": "Coronary Heart Disease (CHD)/Coronary Artery Disease (CAD) Four meta-analyses have investigated the association between dairy products and CHD/CAD risk in the last five years [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Moderate evidence that higher intake of cheese is associated with a moderately reduced risk of CHD was reported by Chen et al. [CITATION_5] . No evidence for a reduction of risk of CHD was found for dairy, milk, fermented dairy, cheese, or yoghurt [CITATION_6] . Moderate evidence suggesting that cheese consumption, in particular, at higher servings, but not total dairy, milk or yoghurt, may be associated with a moderate reduction of risk of CHD was reported by Alexander et al. [CITATION_7] . Finally, moderate evidence, reported by Qin et al. [CITATION_8] , suggests that cheese, but not total dairy or yoghurt, may moderately decrease the risk of CHD.",
